{{DISPLAYTITLE:vVO<sub>2</sub>max}} '''vVO<sub>2</sub>max''' ('''velocity at maximal oxygen uptake''') is an intense running or swimming pace. This is the minimum speed for which the organism's [[VO2max|maximal oxygen uptake]] is reached (after a few minutes of exercise at this intensity); at higher paces, additional [[power (physics)|power]] is entirely delivered by [[Anaerobic exercise|anaerobic]] processes. At this pace, [[blood lactate]] in the muscles reaches levels around 8-10&nbsp;[[Molar concentration|mM]].{{Citation needed|date=October 2015}}
The vVO<sub>2</sub>max of world class middle- and long-distance runners may exceed 24&nbsp;km/h (14.9&nbsp;mph or about 4:00/mile pace), making this speed slightly comparable to 3000&nbsp;m race pace. For many athletes, vVO<sub>2</sub>max may be slightly slower than 1500&nbsp;m or mile race pace.{{Citation needed|date=October 2015}}
==Training== Research by [[:fr:Véronique Billat|Véronique Billat]] has shown that training at vVO<sub>2</sub>max pace improves both '''[[VO2max|VO<sub>2</sub>max]]''' and the economy required to maintain pace at this intensity.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Billat|first=Véronique L.|author2=J. Pierre Koralsztein|title=Significance of the Velocity at VO2max and Time to Exhaustion at this Velocity|journal=Sports Med.|date=Aug 1996|volume=2|pages=90–108|url=http://www.insermu902.com/attachments/018_11.1996-Billat-significance%20of%20velocity%20at%20vo2max-SportMed.pdf|accessdate=27 March 2011|doi=10.2165/00007256-199622020-00004|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321201539/http://www.insermu902.com/attachments/018_11.1996-Billat-significance%20of%20velocity%20at%20vo2max-SportMed.pdf|archive-date=21 March 2012|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Billat|first=Véronique L.|author2=DeMarle, Alexandre |author3=Slawinski, Jean |author4=Paive, Mario |author5= Koralsztein, Jean-Pierre |title=Physical and training characteristics of top-class marathon runners|journal=Medicine & Science in Sports & Exercise|date=December 2001|volume=33|issue=12|url=http://journals.lww.com/acsm-msse/Abstract/2001/12000/Physical_and_training_characteristics_of_top_class.18.aspx|accessdate=27 March 2011|doi=10.1097/00005768-200112000-00018 |pages=2089–2097}}</ref>
Training at vVO<sub>2</sub>max takes the form of interval workouts. For example, 3 x 1000&nbsp;m with 3 minutes recovery between each repetition.
=== Determining vVO<sub>2</sub>max from VO<sub>2</sub>max === The formula from Léger and Mercier<ref name="Léger-">{{Cite journal | last1 = Léger | first1 = L. | last2 = Mercier | first2 = D. | title = Gross energy cost of horizontal treadmill and track running. | journal = Sports Med | volume = 1 | issue = 4 | pages = 270–7 | doi = 10.2165/00007256-198401040-00003| PMID = 6390604 | year=1984}}</ref> links the VO<sub>2</sub>max to the vVO<sub>2</sub>max, supposing an ideal running technique.
:vVO<sub>2</sub>max = VO<sub>2</sub>max / 3.5 where vVO<sub>2</sub>max is in km/h and VO<sub>2</sub>max is in mL/(kg•min).
'''Note''': This formula is identical to that used to calculate the [[Metabolic_equivalent|Metabolic Equivalent of Task (MET)]] score for a given VO<sub>2</sub>max estimation.
